Now, we will first compute for the cash flow to creditors.

$$\begin{aligned}
 \text{Cash Flow to Creditors} &= \text{Interest Paid} - {\text{Net New Borrowings}}\\[5pt] 
&= \text{\$255,000} - {\text{340,000}}\\[5pt] 
&= \underline{\underline{\textbf{(\$85,000)}}} 
\end{aligned}

Next, we will calculate for the cash flow to shareholders.

$$\begin{aligned} 
\text{Cash Flow to Shareholders} &= \text{Dividends Paid} - {\text{Net New Equity raised}}\\[5pt] 
&= \text{\$545,000} - {\text{375,000}}\\[5pt] 
&= \underline{\underline{\textbf{\$170,000}}}
\end{aligned}

Before we compute for the OCF, we need to compute first the Cash flow from assets using the information above:

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Cash flow from assets} &= \text{ Cash flow to creditors} + {\text{Cash flow to shareholders}}\\[5pt]
&= \text{-\$85,000} + {\text{170,000}}\\[5pt]
&= \underline{\underline{\textbf{\$85,000}}}
\end{aligned}$$
